{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600623/1930081901/0195.xml":{"full_text":"A-2\nWAR SERVICE WINS\nAID FOR CAMPBELL\nV. F. W. Post Retains Counsel\nfor Baker Murder Suspect\non Eve of Hearing.\nHte military service on the Mexican\nborder in 1916 and in Prance a few\nyears later has won for Herbert M.\nCampbell the legal aid of the Veterans\nof Foreign Wars, with which organiza\ntion the indicted suspect in the Mary\nBaker murder case is affiliated.\nHerbert S. Ward, co-resident in Ar\nlington County with the accused war\nveteran and practitioner of law in the\nDistrict, has been designated by Fed\neral Tost No. 824. Veterans of Foreign\n\u25a0Wars, as \"special advocate\" to assist in\nCampbells defense.\nWard has conferred by telephone with\nCharles Henry Smith, attorney retained\nby the Campbell family, who is on a\nmysterious mission out of town. It is\nunderstood the veterans' counsel will\nmake his first appearance in the case\nwhen Campbell is srraigned before\nUnited States Commissioner J. Barton\nPhillips in Alexandria tomorrow morn\ning at 10 o'clock.\nLively Battle Expected.\nThe preliminary hearing in the com\nmissioner\u2019s office is expected to develop\ninto a lively legal battle between op- j\nposing counsel, with the Government\nseeking Campbell immediate removal\nto the District, Jail and the defense op\nposing the move with every power in its\nmeans.\nShould the defense succeed in turn\ning the hearing into a virtual prelim\ninary' trial on the merits of the case\nagainst the real estate man. Federal\ncounsel are said to have \"something up\nthe sleeve\u201d intended to prove a surprise\nto the defense. The nature of the \u2018sur\nprise\u201d was not disclosed, although it is\nunderstood to affect several of Camp\nbell'S alibi witnesses.\nIn the meantime Albert H Hamilton,\nAuburn. N. Y.. criminologist, who is re\nported to have offered his services as\na ballistics expert to the defense, in\njected an element of mystery into this\nphase of the case today by advising\nThe Star of activities of \"a stranger\"\nInterested in ballistic angles of the\nBaker probe.\nAnswered Specific Questions.\nAccording to a telegraphic explana\ntion of his connection with the Baker\ncase. Hamilton said that \"specific\nscientific questions in ballistics\u201d in\nvolved in the case had been submitted\nto him by the \u201cstranger.\u201d He said he\nhad replied to these questions, but he\nfailed to divulge the name of the\nstranger, the nature of the queries made\nand the reply submitted.\nIf Hamilton is retained as a defense\nexpert, he will meet with opposition\nfrom the Government in any move to\nexamine in his New York laboratory\nCampbell\u2019s gun and the fatal bullets:\nAssistant United States Attorney Wil\nliam H. Collins said today the prosecu\ntion would never consent to this evi\ndence leaving the Government's posses\nsion. If Hamilton is willing to exam\nine the gun and bullets at the Bureau\nof Standards in the presence of Dr.\nWilmer Souder, the plan will be con\nsidered. he said. It is thought unlikely\nHamilton would consent to examine the\nweapon with any instruments but his\nown. however.\nAttorney Ward said today that Camp\nbell enlisted July 8, 1916, in this city\nwith Company C. 113th Field Signal\nBattalion, serving on the Mexican bor\nder until March 12, 1917, and contin\nuing In the service until May 16, 1919,\nwhen he was honorably discharged as\na corporal by reason of demobilization.\nDuring this enlistment he served over\nseas in the World War. After the war\nhe again enlisted and was finally dis\ncharged January 1, 1925, as corporal,\nthe attorney stated.\n10 BODIES ARE FOUND\nIN BLAKEBURN MINE\n\nRescue Squad to Continue Search\nWhere 45 Workers Were En\ntombed Last Wednesday.\nBy the Auociated Frtsi.\nBLAKEBURN, British Columbia Au\nguat 19. \u2014Ten bodies were found last\nnight In the Blakebum Mine, where\n45 workers were entombed in an ex\nplosion last Wednesday. Three bodies\npreviously had been recovered.\nRescue workers returning to the pit\nhead Just before midnight announced\nthe bodies were located on No. 1 store.\nOther bodies had been found near the\npit portal.\nRescuers had penetrated quite a dis\ntance from where they were tem\nporarily halted by Friday's fire. No\nattempts were made to identify the\ndead men. Workers said, with cave\nins blocking the stope. it might be\nseveral days before the bodies could be\nbrought out.\nGLADYS O\u2019DONNELL\nSTILL IN LEAD OF\nWOMEN\u2019S AIR DERBY\n<Continued From First Page.)\nMooney and Earl Rowland of Wichita,\nrace entrants, had not appeared.\nThe race was for class B planes of\nless than 500 cubic inches piston dis\nplacement.. fiown from Los Angeles to\nNew York last year end won by Living\neton. Rowland won the class A event Tn\n1928\nThe itinerary and schedule:\nDeparture from Brownsville at 9 am.,\nrefueling at Corpus Christ! and Houston\nand night stop at San Antonio; Wed\nnesday. refueling at Waco, night stop at\nFort Worth: Thursday, refueling at\nWichita Falls and Oklahoma City with\nnight stop at Tulsa: Friday, refueling at\nSpringfield, Mo\u201e and night stop at St,\nLouis; Saturday, refueling at Aurora.\n111., and finish at Chicago.\nBIG ARMADA TO ELY.\nEighty Plane* Will Swoop Down on\nChicago From St. Louis.\nCHICAGO. August 19 (A*). \u2014An ar\nmada from the South and Southwest\nwill fly from St. Louis Friday for the\nwelcome to famous flyers entered In\nthe natlonsl sir races.\nA squadron of 80 planes, privately\nowned, will gather in St. Louis Thurs\nday for the maneuver, The armada is\ndue over Chicago's Loop at noon, where\nit will join squadrons of Army, Navy\nand Marine Corps ships. Below, the\nvisiting famous flyers of America and\nEurope will be escorted down ticker\ntape lanes.\nMaj. R. W. Schroeder. contest direc\ntor of the races, said three entrants\nwere assured for the take-off tomorrow\nof the nun s derby for 200 horsepower\nplanes from Miami.\nMaj Schroeder also announced that\nthe take-off for the non-stop race from\nLas Angeles to Chicago would be made\nany day of the race after Sunday, de\npending upon weather conditions.\nCoste\u2019n Radio It 0. K.\nLE BOURGET, Fiance, August 19\n(jpi.\u2014Dieudonne Coste. French aviation\nace, in a flight over Le Bourget Field\nthis morning tested his plane's new\nwireless equipment and pronounced\nhimself fully satisfied. He said he was\nready to set out on his projected At\nltntig flight to New York at the first\ni\u00bbw oaem weather reports favorable.\nGREET FIRST PI.ANF, OF NEW YORK-CAPITAL AIR LINE\n\n_\nf\u2019\u25a0\u25a0l[9HhKHs\u00dfh|9Ek a apl 1 aBB\nLeft to tight: C H. Frame. Paul J. Leverone and Lieut. Walter Hinton, chairman of the aviation committee of the\nWashington Chamber of Commerce E. W. Parker, pilot: Thomas Carroll, vice president of Washington Airport, and C. W.\nj Freitag, also of the Chamber of Commerce. The picture was taken shortly after Pilot Parker had set down the big Ford\n1 transport at Washington Airport yesterday morning. II was the first ship on a daily plane service between New York,\nWashington and Richmond, being run by the Eastern Air Transport. Star Staff Photo.\nWOMEN IN POLITICS DISAPPOINT\nMRS. BLAIR, SUFFRAGE LEADER\nI \u2014\u2014i\u2014\u2014\u25a0 I n\u00ab i\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u00bbQ\u2014*\u2014\u2014\u2014o\u2014\n'Views of Notables, Gathered\nfor Anniversary of Bal\nlot, Vary.\n\nMany Feel Neither Highest\nHopes Nor Worst Fears\nRealized.\nBy the Associated Press.\nEmily Newell Blair, who campaigned\nfor suffrage in Mftsouri back in 1914.\nis \u201cfrankly quite discouraged about\nwomen In politics.\u201d\nShe made this known today in her\ncontribution\u2014the first pessimistic one\u2014\nto a fat compendium of opinions on\nwomen and the ballot gathered by the\nLeague t Women voers to mark the\ntenth birthday of feminine suffrage in\nAmerica.\nView* Gathered for Anniversary.\nAll these views, gathered from no\ntables of both sexes, are to be published\nfor the anniversary on August 26 of the\nsigning by former Secretary of State\nColby of the proclamation that actually\nculminated the movement.\n\u201cI am afraid,\u201d Mrs. Blair said, \u201cthe\nsuffragists have made the same mia\nj take as the temperance group. Both\nof them thought that with their victory\nthey had only to defend their position;\nand so. just as the Women's Christian\nTemperance Union stopped its educa\ntional work for temperance and devoted\nitself to claiming the eighteenth amend\nment worked, so the suffragists stopped\ntheir educational work of convincing\npeople that Women had a right to equal-\nity and devoted themselves to other in\nterests.\u201d\nMary E. Woolley, president of Mount\nHolyoke College, In responding to the\nleague\u2019s query, said:\n\u201cThe granting of the suffrage to\u00ab\nwomen has not brought about the mil\nlenium, but it has meant a decided step\ntoward better government.\nThere are indifferent citizens among\nwomen as among men, but the addition\nof women certainly has meant a large\nIncrease In the number of citizens who\nare both conscientious and intelligent.\u201d\nEducational Processes Lauded.\nSaid Newton D. Baker, former War\nSecretary: \u201c\u2019\u00a3he years of experience\nunder the nineteenth amendment are\nnot enough to enable me to express any\npositive Judgments as to the use which j\nI women In general have made of their\nsuffrage privilege.\u201d I\nBLACK, WORLD FLYER,\nMISSING FROM YACHT\nOFF JERSEY COAST\n<Continued From First Page.)\ncrossed the Pacific on shipboard and\nthen flew to Baltimore from San Fran\ncisco.\nVan Lear Black was known inter\nnationally as an aviation enthusiast I\nand there were many places in far\nflung parts of the earth that he and\nhis plane were known. He was not a\nflyer himself, but used passenger planes\nand had his own pilots and mechanics.\nCruisin\u00df by air. much as yacht own\ners cruised by sea, Mr. Black traveled\nthousands of miles over Europe. Africa\nand Asia during the past few years\nand probably held the world record for\nmiles flown as a passenger. He was\nintensely interested In the commercial\npossibilities of aviation and on his trips\ncarefully studied the progress of air\ntravel.\nAlthough he had traveled thousands\nof miles by air. his trips were singularly\nfree from trouble or accident. In ail\nhe had two crashes. One in Genoa in\nApril, 1929, and the second at Calcutta\nIn June of that year.\nBegan Globe Trip in 1928.\nHis first well known flight was from\nHolland to the Dutch East Indies in\n1927. In 1928 he began a world flight,\nbut gave it up in Egypt when trouble\ndeveloped. He then returned to the\nUnited States after having toured 20\nnations by air.\nLater in 1928 he again started on an\nAfrican air jaunt from Europe and flew\nto Nairobi in Kenya Colony, then re\nturning again to Europe by air. It\nwas while on his wav back to London\nthat he had his first forced landing at\nGenoa.\nIn May. 1929. he started on a flight\nfrom London to Tokto, this trip ending\nwhen his plane was cracked up on\nlanding at Calcutta. Undaunted, he\nstarted again this year and this time\nsucceeded in flying to Tokio. From\nTokio he sailed for San Francisco and\narrived back in Baltimore on May 19.\nTORIES ARE EXPECTED\nTO SEIZE JOBLESS ISSUE j\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nLONDON. August 19.- Well informed\npolitical circles assert that Tory poli\nticians are preparing a heavy campaign\nagainst Ramsay MacDonalds Socialist\ngovernment, basing their chief talking i\npoint on the failure of the Laborites to\nsolve unemployment.\nWith 2.000,000 w'orkless clamoring for j\nrelief, the Conservative leaders are\nunderstood to be planning to strike I\nwhile unrest Is high. The present un\nemployment figures break all previous\nBritish records and word has been\npassed around Conseivative stronghold*\nto try to force a general election before 1\nthe tide turns. i\nNext month will see the beginning of\nthe Tory bombardment and when Par\nliament reassemble* October 28 all\nparties are likely to be prepared for a\nVltAl division.\nTHE E\\ EKING STAR, WASHINGTON. D. C., TL ESP AY, ALA. IST 19, 1930.\n.^nn\nCIVIII.Y NEWELL BI.AIR.\n.le added, however, that educational\nprocesses women have set up to train\nthemsplves seemed to him \"admirable\nin spirit and accomplishment\" and that\n\"a great question of political right was\nsettled.\"\nMrs. Raymond Brown, editor of the\nWoman's Journal, gave as her opinion\nthat \"both men and women arc ques-\nj tioning Government processes and are\nwatching the actions of elected officials\ni as they used to do\u201d and that \u201cpolitical\nparty committees and candidates have\ntrequentlv been embarrassed and some\ntimes incensed at the questions women\nhave showered on them.\u201d j\ni Mrs. Franklin Roosevelt said women\n1 had made \u201ca contribution to better\ngovernment\" and that \u201cwlierever they\nhave taken part in local politics there\ni is no question but what the general\nstandards have gone up.\" She con\ntended \u201cthe percentage of those who\nuse their suffrage is probably about\nequal now to the percentage of men\nj who use theirs.\"\nNeilsott Speak* for Many.\nDr. W. A. Neilson, president of Bmith\nCollege, put into words what many who\nwere consulted seemed to feel. He said i\n\u201cit is a commonplace that no great po-\nlitical change produces all the evils Its\nopponents predicted or all the good its\nsupporters hoped for.\" In his obser-\nration, he added, fears of the opponents\nof woman's suffrage \"have been realized\nhardly at all,\u201d while the high hopes of\nits supporters \u201care being gradually but\ni steadily fulfilled.\u201d\nPEPCO BUILDING\nVALUE IN PARLEY\nConference Held on Rating of\nProperty Bought by Fed\neral Government.\nOfficials of the Potomac Electric j\nPower Co. met with the Public Utilities\nCommission today in an effort to iron\nout a difference which has arisen over\na figure at which the power company's\noffice building and power station at\nFourteenth and B streets, which has\nbeen bought by the Federal Govern\nment, shall be retired from the com\npany's valuation.\nThe property was bought by the\nGovernment last January for *3.600.000\nIts \u201cbook cost\" Is slightly in excess of j\n*2,400.000. and the company proposes\nto retire it at this figure.\nIn 1924 the commission nnd the com-\npany compromised over value by taking\na figure of approximately 25 per cent j\nmore than the book cost, to represent j\nvaluation. The commission's conten- j\ntion is now that the property should j\nbe retired at at least this increase over\nbook cost, which would make the re- i\ntirement. in round figures *3.000,000. I\nOtherwise, the commission argues, there j\nwill be left in the valuation figure 1\nsome *600.000. not representing any i\nproperty on which the public will be\nrequired to pay a reasonable return In\nthe way of electric rates. Even if the j\ncommission's figures prevail, there would 1\nstill be left some *600.000 as the dll- j\nference between their figure and the\nprice at which the property changed I\nhands.\nThe conference was held behind j\nclosed doors and after it was over it\nwas announced that no decision had\nyet been reached.\n\u201cELOPERS\u201d FOUND DEAD\nMarried Man and Girl, 15, Missing;\nSince Last October.\nMEDICINE HAT, Alberta, August 19 j\n(>P).\u2014 Adam Snyder, a married man, and I\n1 15-vear-old Minnie Sturm disappeared\nlast October in Snyder's car and were\nthought to have eloped.\nTheir bodies were found by a rider i\nSunday lying in the car which was hid- j\nden from view- in a mountain coulee. A\nnote beside them said they took poison\ntogether.\nICE HOLDS PATROL SHIP\ni j\nProgress of Steamer Blocked 50\nMiles From Far North Post.\nNORTH SYDNEY. Nova Scotia, Au\ngust 19 t/Pj.\u2014The steamship Boethic,\nArctic patrol ship which left North j\nSydney at the end of July, in fast in\nthe ice about 50 miles from Boche\nPeninsula, the farthest northern post\nto receive the yearly provisioning.\nFurther progress is impossible until the\nice loosens, a radio dispatch said.\nVETERANS OF 1898\nHEAR NAVAL PLEA\nMen of Spanish War Urged\nto Support Present Build\ning Program.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPHILADELPHIA August 19.\u2014A plea\nfor support of the Navy\u2019s building pro\ngram was made today before the thirty\nsecond annual encampment of the\nUnited SpanLsh War Veterans as the j\n\u201cboys of '9B\u201d gathered at their head- j\nquarters in preparation for the military\nparade later in the afternoon.\nCapt. W. C. Watts of the Philadelphia 1\ni Navy Yard, and who for two years was\nin command of the U. S. S. Colorado, j\nwas the speaker. He sketched the prog- i\nless of naval affairs from the time of\nthe doughty old Olympia, Admiral\nDewey's flagship, to the present. He\nurged the veterans to support the build\ning program of the Navy, declaring that\nits importance could not be overesti\n-1 mated.\nI A group of Spanish War nurses ap\n-1 peared on the platform at the conclu\nsion of Capt. Watts' address to present\na bouquet to Fred W. Green, Governor\nof Michigan and national commander\nof the veterans\u2019 organization. Among\nthe nurses were Miss Rebecca Horn, Las\nAngeles, and Mrs. Elizabeth E. Dentping,\ni Long Beach, Calif.\nPROBE IN IMPROPER\nRAIDS IS ORDERED\nBY CHIEF OF POLICE\n(Continued Prom First Page.)\n11 people, papers were refused because\nof warrantless raids, while in the other j\ntwo papers were refused because of in-\nsufficient evidence.\nHart has consistently refused to\ncountenance cases in which the charge*\ngrew out of warrantless raids and has\nalso discouraged the use of \"stool\npigeons,\u201d special informers and similar\nagents used in gathering prohibition\ni violation information. The prosecutor\nhas made every effort, he said, to com\npel officers to secure warrants before\nattempting to enter any premises.\nSeveral of the police who had papers\nrefused by the prosecutor yesterday dis\nplayed displeasure at the stand taken\nby Hart, but the attorney remained firm\nin his refusal to make out cases against\npersons seized on insufficient evidence\nor during an illegal raid.\nTwo Dry Cases Reported Today.\nThe smallest number of liquor cases\nin recent weeks was reported to Hart's\noffice today, when only two alleged vio\nlations of liquor law cases were brought\nto the attorney\u2019s attention. Hart re-\nfused papers in one of these cases be\ncause of insufficient evidence.\nFollowing a raid on premises in the\n400 block of New York avenue. Hunter\nLee Jenkins, colored. 39. of the above\naddress, was arrested and charged with\npossession of h\u00dflf a pint of whisky.\nJenkins pleaded guilty and was sen\ntenced by Judge Robert E. Mattingly to\npay a fine of *SO or to serve 60 days in\njail. The raid was conducted by Po\nlicemen E. L. Shelton and C. N. Strange\nj of the second precinct.\nAttorney Hart refused papers in the\ncase of Ernest Womack, colored, 32,\nj of the 600 block of O street, after he\nwas arrested yesterday on charges of\npossession of liquor. Police said they\nhad a \"tip\u201d that liquor was being de\nlivered at Womack's home. Police said\nthey looked through a keyhole and saw\nWomack filling a bottle with colored\nliquid. They waited until Womack\ncame out and asked him what he was\ndoing with liquor. Womack is said to\nhave answered that it was for his own I\nuse, but refused to tell police why he j\nhad extra bottles and a funnel in his\nj room.\nINFORMER WILL TESTIFY.\nThe usual custom of virtually disre-\nI garding evidence collected by prohlbi\nj tion Informers in liquor cases at Police\nCourt will undergo a change today when\n1 Assistant United States Attorney David\nA. Hart places an informer on the wit\nness stand to testify against Ernest Me-\nCall Jeffries of the 1300 bloi-k of Massa\nchusetts avenue.\nThe prosecutor placed Joseph Burke,\n1 Informer, on the stand to testify that he\nmade a \"buy\u201d from Jeffries at his home\nMay 6.\nJeffries, who is chargea with main\nj taining a nuisance and two counts of\n1 second-offense possession of liquor, was\nfirst arrested on a liquor law violation\nI in 1928.\nOn April 16 an informer went to\nJeffries home and made a \u201cbuy\u201d with\nmarked money. A raid followed and\nJeffries was arrested on liquor charges,\nj The marked money, police said, was\ni found on his person\nAttorney Hart said that on May 6\nBurke was sent to Jeffries home and\nsucceeded in making a liquor purchase.\nA second raid followed and a quantity\nof liquor w'as seized. Attorney Hart\nsaid that Burke will testify to the effect\nthat he was successful in making a ptfr\nchase at Jeffries' home.\nJeffries\u2019 case opened this morning\nl at Police Court before Judge Isaac\nR. Hitt. The raids on Jeffries\u2019 home\ni were conducted by Lieut. O. J. Letter\nman of the sixth precinct, who at the\ntime was head of the police vice squad.\nSecond precinct police, headed by\nCapt. O. T. Davis of the second pre- 1\ncinct, also figured in the raids on Jes-\nfries .home. Both .Capt. Davis and\nLimit. Letterman will tastily against\nJeffriea.\nRETIRED OFFICERS\nGIVEN WAR RANK\nBliss and March Become Full\nGenerals as Result of Re\ncent Legislation.\nIn accordance with the provisions of\nj the act of Congress approved June 21,\ni last, the War Department today an-\nI nounced the advancement of all the\nofficers of the Army on the retired list\nto the rank in which they served tem\nporarily during the World War. Heading\nthe list are Maj. Gen. Tasker H. Bliss\nand Maj. Gen. Peyton C. March, former\nchiefs of staff of the Army during that\nperiod, who consequently have been ad\nvanced to the rank of full general\nThere are about 700 names in the\nlist of retired officers thus advanced in\ncluding more than 100 who have been\nadvanced to the various ranks of\ngeneral.\nNo Pay Change.\nGen. Bliss and Gen. March will rc- j\nceive the retired pay of $6,000, the law j\nhaving authorized no change in pav\nwith the advancement in rank. Os the\nvarious officers who served as full gen\nerals during the W\u2019orld War, Gen. Per-\nshing was the only one who retained\nthat rank after the armistice. Gen.\nBliss succeeded Gen. Hugh L. Scott, as\nchief of staff just before the outbreak\nof the war.\nBrig. Gen. John Biddle, who has\nbeen advanced to the rank of major\ngeneral, retired, was acting thief of\nstaff until the appointment of Gen.\nMarch, who served from March 4. 1918,\nto 1921. Aside from his military duties,\nGen. Bliss was a member of the Amer\nican Peace Commission that met at\nVersailles and concluded the terms that,\nended the war with Germany.\nOthers Are Listed.\nOther general officers on the list\nwere advanced as follows:\nTo the rank of lieutenant general\u2014\nMaj. Gens. Hunter Liggett and Robert,\nL. Bullard.\nTo the rank of major general\u2014\nBrig. Gens. George T. Bartlett, Richard\nM. Blatchford and Augustus P. Block\nsom. Col. Beaumont B. Buck. Brig. Gen.\nWilliam P. Burnham. Cols. George H.\nCameron and Guy Carleton. Brig. Gens.\nEdwin St. J. Greble, Henry C. Hodges,\njr.; Henry Jervev and Chase W. Ken\nnedy, Col. William C. Langfitt and\nBrig. Gens. William A. Mann, James\nParker, Frederick S. Strong. Eben\nSwift, Peter E. Traub, Charles G. Treat\nand Edmund Wittemyer.\nTo the rank of brigadier general\u2014\nCols. Frank H. Albright, William H.\nAllaire, Edward Anderson and Edward\nD. Anderson. Lieut. Col. Lincoln C. An\ndrews. Cols. William 11. Arthur. Chaun\ncey B. Baker and Frank E. Hamford,\nMaj. Charles W. Barber, Cols. John B.\nBennet, I.ucien G. Berry, Henry P.\nBirmingham, George Blakely, John J.\nBradley and Robert A. Brown, Lieut.\nCol. Beverly F. Browne, Cols. Edward\nBurr. Vernon A Caldwell and Edward\nR Chrlsman. Lieut. Col. Marlborough\nChurchill. Cols. William B. Cochran,\nCharles Crawford, James J. Hornbrook.\nHarold P. Howard. Ora E. Hunt and\nGeorge K. Hunter. Maj. Charles C.\nJamieson, Cols. Arthur Johnson. Jeffer\nson R. Kean, Charles Keller and Daniel\nW Ketcham. Lieut. Col. John W. Kil\nbreth. Cols. Albert D. Knlskern. FraneU\nJ. Koester, Charles W. Kutz, James R.\nLindsay, P. D. Lochridge, Rufus E.\nLongan, Thedore C. Lyster, John S.\nMallory, William F. Martin, Frank G.\nMauldin, Nathaniel F. McClure,\nGeorge W. Mclver, Charles H. Mc-\nKinstry, Clarence H. McNeil, Rob\nert W. Mearns, Edward A. Mil\nlar, Samuel W. Miller, Jay J.\nMorrow, Benjamin C. Morse,\nPeter Murrav. Henry C. Newcomer.\nGeorge O. Cress, Marcus D. Cronin,\nWilliam R. Dashiell, William C. Davis,\nFrederick R. Day. James T. Dean. Dan\niel B. Devore, Charles B, Drake. Lucius\nL. Durfee, Frederic D. Evans, William\nM. Fassett, Adrian S. Fleming, Freder\nick S. Foltz. Joseph A. Gaston, George\nW. Gatchell, Charles Gerhardt, Robert\nN. Getty. Thomas G. Hanson, John\nD. L. Hartman, Everard E. Hatch. John\nL. Hayden, Charles A. Hedekin, Gordon\nG. Heiner, Robert- N. Noble. Joseph P\nO\u2019Neil, Julius A. Penn Frederick Per\nkins, Charles L. Phillips. Palmer E\nPierce. Guy H. Preston, William C. Raf\nferty. Thomas H. Rees, John H. Rice.\nCharles Richard, j\u00dfmes A. Ryan.\nFarrand Sayre, Benjamin T. Sim\nmons, Alfred A. Starbird, Henry D\nStyer, John T. Thompson, Orval P\nTownshend, Robert C. Van Vleit,\nCharles C. Walcutt, jr.. and Frank D\nWebster. Lieut. Col. William I. Wester\nyelt. Cols. Charles B Wheeler, Henry\nH. Whitney. Harry E Wilkins, John S\nWinn and Francis A Winter, Maj. Rob\nert E. Wood and Col. William T. Wood\nChess Champion Plays 23.\nLIEGE. Belgium, August 19 LP). \u2014Dr.\nAlexander Alekhine of Paris, chess\nchampion of the world, played against\n23 volunteer players simultaneously yes\nterday In the formal opening of the In\nternational Chess Congress. After three\nhours and a half, the champion wound\nup with a score of 21 wins and 2 losses.\nCrooner lo Wed\nAms\n\nw\nBl jB\ngH jLjSjj y\u00dfmfe.\nWill Osborne. the eroonin* orchestra\nleader, and Margaret Ekdahl, beauty I\ncontest winner l( \u00abfho have taken friends\nby surprise in the announcement of\ntheir intention to marry.\nA MERMAID DISPLAYS HER TROPHIES\nin<Byi -Mil\nHMf r C ill\nW* 'MMF flk \u00bbH\u2122\u00a7:na mjhM ~mk M\n:MWd J ~F r i^M\u00a7 J1 Wm. -SBBm\n?*sf flll lriMi:i \u00abMB|E 1\nAABMbP\njj\njMg&gSf Mm Mm%1.l 'l*'r< '\u00bb~4*' r*Ssfe<jJM\nV\nWhen Miss Olive Hatrh, swimming star of the Los Angeles Athletic Club,\ngathers together all the cups and medals she has won they make a fair nucleus\nfor a jewelry store! Among other distinctions as a swimmer, she is a member of\nthe national championship women\u2019s 880-yard relay team, which recently set a\nnew world's record. Miss Hatch is competing next month in the Far Western\nlA.A. U. swimming championships at San Francisco. Associated Press Phcto.\nPERILS OF RESCUE\nFROM TAHITI TOLD\nPassengers Praise Captains\nfor Seamanship in\nTrying Hours.\nI By the Associated Press.\nWELLINGTON, New Zealand, August\n19. \u2014First stories from passengers of the\nill-fated Pacific passenger liner Tahiti,\nreaching here today from Pago Pago,\nindicated that masterly seamanship on\nthe part of the captains of both the\nTahiti and the rescue ship Ventura pre\nvented an appalling disaster.\nOrdered to Lifeboats Twice.\nTwice before the Ventura arrived,\nwhen there seemed no hope of rescue at\nhand, the Tahiti's captain gave orders\nto the passengers to take to the life\nboats.\nAll aboard the Tahiti were grateful\nfor what appeared to be their deliver\nance when the freighter Penybryn hove\nabove the horizon and made her way to\na point near the distressed Tahiti, but\nalthough she stood by and was willing\nto do all possible to succor the disabled\nand sinking craft, the Penvbrvn lacked\nequipment to transfer the Tahiti's com\npany.\nFear ruled the Tahiti for three days,\nbut throughout their harrowing experi\nence the passengers were orderly and\nobedient to the dictates of wiser minds.\nWhen the great good fortune of rescue\ncame to them the woman passengers\nfirst were transferred, then the men and\nfinally the crew.\nAttempt Made to Save Mail.\nWhen all hands were aboard the\nVentura, an attempt was made to save\nthe vast quantities of mail in her\nholds.\nWith some of the bags already taken\noff, ship\u2019s boats were returning for\nmore when the Tahiti lurched and\ntook another roll.\nThe waves swept over her bows,\nwhich failed to rise again from be\nneath the water. Then the doomed\nliner straightened on an even keel.\nHer stern rose and she disappeared in\na boiling white whirlpool.\nThere was a mass of splintered up\nper w'orks still floating as the Ventura\nsteamed away.\nAmericans Due at Pago Pago.\nPAGO PAGO, August 19.-\u2014The liner\nVentura was due at this American naval\nbase at 1 p.m. today (5:30 p.m., P. S. T.)\nwith the 317 persons rescued from the\nj British steamer Tahiti, which went\ni down in the South Pacific yesterday\nafter being in distress for three days.\nOs the 317 persons rescued, 149 mem\nbers of the Tahltti\u2019s crew and 16 pas\nsengers will disembark here. The other\npassengers will continue to San Fran\ncisco aboard the Ventura.\nRESCUE SHIP ENDANGERED.\nWELLINGTON, New Zealand, August\n19 (A>). \u2014The Norwegian freighter Peny\nbryn, which sped to aid the distressed\nliner Tahiti in the South Pacific this\nweek, was Itself in danger today.\nThe freighter, carrying sugar from\nCuba to Auckland, is now running short\nof coal and is afraid to face an on\ncomi a shr c mfw rd\ncoming southwest gale It must battle\nto reach the New Zealand port. The\nvessel is endeavoring to reach Suva, in\nthe Fijis, for recoaling.\nTOP-GRADE AIR PILOTS\nEARN $550 PER MONTH\nAeronautic Officials, Commerce De\npartment Report Average Paid\nin Mail and Passenger Service.\nBy the Associated Press.\nAverage wages now being earned bv\nairplane pilots of the highest capability\nclass range around $550 per month.\nThe aeronautic branch of the Com\nmerce Department ascertained the\nI flight pay as a result of a survey of\npay rolls of air mail and passeriger-\nI carrying enterprises for the first six\nmonths of 1930 and the last, half of\n1929. The pilots In this service are\nholders of the highest class of license,\nobtained only after much experience\nand training.\nIn almost all cases, earnings of such\npilots arc based upon mileage flown.\nThe compilations indicated the aver\nage pilot In these services received the\nstraight salary averaging $lB9 pe:\nmonth and, in addition, 5 cents per mile\nfor day flying and 10 cents per mile\nfor night flying. The top wages of\nSBSO were received by a group of mail\npilots regularly flying ta night.\nMechanics servicing planes and\nengines on air routes, the compilation\nalso showed, average during the same\nperiod $157 per month, the average\nwage running around 74 cents per hour.\nBAND CONCERT.\nBy the United States Soldiers\u2019 Home\nMilitary Band, this evening, at the\nbandstand, at 5:30 o\u2019clock. John S. M.\nZimmermann, bandmaster; Anton Point\nner, assistant:\nMarch, \u201cThe American Army\u201d...lnstill\nOverture, \u201cLea Huguenots\". .Meyerbeer\nEntr'acte\u2014\nSong of the Boatmen of the Volga.\"\n\u201cLa Bella Zlngara\u201d Roberto\nExcerpts from comic opera \"Boccaccio,\u201d\nSuppe\nFox-trot, \"Sweeping the Clouds Away,\u201d\nCoslow\nWalt* suite, \"Pleasures of the Past.\u201d\nWaldteufei\nFinale, \"Give Yourself a Pat on the\nBack\" .\u2019Wallace\n\u201cThe Star Spangled Banner.\u201d\nGOV. RITCHIE CALLS\nDROUGHT MEETING\nBanking, Railroad and Farm\ning Leaders to Consider Re\nlief at Parley Friday.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBALTIMORE, August 19.\u2014Repre\nsentatives of Maryland banking, rail\nroad and agricultural fields have been\ncalled into conference by Gov. Albert\nC. Ritchie to discuss means for allevia\ntion of drought-stricken sections of the\nI State where a survey shows crop losses\nI ranging from s(h- per cent to total loss.\nThe meeting of industrial leaders was\nset for Friday.\n5 At the same time It became known\nPresident Hoover had replied to Sen\n-1 ator Phillips Lee Goldsborough\u2019s plea\nthat Maryland be included In Federal\nrelief plans, declaring the State would\nbe welcome to participate with others\nin the program outlined at a conference\nof Governors to which the Maryland\nI executive was not invited. Gov. Ritchie\nI had protested Maryland\u2019s exclusion.\nThe State Industrialists will meet\nfollowing a drought conference of the\nMaryland State Grange set for Wednes\nday. Out of the two meetings is ex\npected to come a definite program for\naid to the affected sections.\nHOOVER APPOINTS\nHYDE CHAIRMAN OF\nDROUGHT RELIEF\nContinued From First Page.)\ning to and from drought rones will be\nsent to railroad officials for final ap- j\nproval before establishment of the,\nemergency rates.\nA list of counties in four States was\nadded to those in which emergency\nrates have been authorized. These,\ncounties includes\nWyoming\u2014Campbell, Johnson, Sheri- 1\ndan and Weston.\nLouisiana \u2014Avoyelles. Bienville, Bos\nsier, Caddo, Caldwell, Catahoula, Clai\nborne, Concordia, East Baton Rouge.\nEast Carroll, East Feliciana, Franklin,\nGrant. Jackson, La Salle, Lincoln,\nMadison. Morehouse. Natchitoches,\nOuachita, Red River. Richland, Sabine,\nSt. Helena. Tangipahoa, Tensas, Union, j\nWashington, Webster, West Carroll and\nWinn.\nMontana \u2014Big Horn. Blaine, Carbon, I\nCascade, Chouteau, Fergus, Gallatin.\nGarfield. Golden Valley, Hill. Judith 1\nBasin, Liberty, Madison. Musselshell,\nPark, Petroleum, Phillips, Powder River.\nRosebud, Stillwater,Sweetgrass,Treasure,\nValley, Wheatland and Yellowstone.\nOklahoma-Atoka, Choctaw. Coal,\nJohnston, Latimer, LaFlore, McCurtain. I\nMclntosh, Pittsburgh, Pushmataha and\nSequoyah.\nFAIR FORECAST HERE.\nMiddle West to Get Showers as Drought\nContinues Near Capital.\nContinued fair weather, with cool\ntemperatures, forecast by the Weather\nBureau for tomorrow, give no indica\ntion of any rains, it was said, during\nthe next few days to relieve the effects\nof the drought in Washington and\nneighboring Maryland and Virginia dis\ntricts.\nOther sections, however, will fare bet\nter. Showers over a large portion of the\nMiddle West were reported to the\nWeather Bureau today, with predictions\nof further rains in the northern por\ntion of the dry area tonight and to\nmorrow.\nj Bureau officials said precipitation of\nthe last 24 hours had extended over\nareas not previously touched by rains\nI since the drought became acute, in\ncluding Southern North Dakota and\nmost of South Dakota.\nRains were reported general over\nEastern Kansas and extreme Eastern\nNebraska, extreme Western lowa,\nSouthern and Western Missouri. Mis\nsissippi and most of Arkansas and\nLouisiana.\nShowers also were reported in West\nern Alabama and Western Tennessee.\nAdditional rains in lowa and Minne\nsota and North Dakota were forecast\nfor tonight and tomorrow.\nBismarck. N. Dak., and Huron, S.\nDak., reported 0.34 and 0.98 inches of\nrainfall, respectively, in the last 24\nhoui Omaha, Nebr., had 0.56 Inches.\nSioux City, lowa, JDM, Kansas City,\n0.92, and Springfield, Mo, 0.74.\nSLICK FUNERAL HELD\nMany Oil Operators Attend Rites\nHeld at Clarion, Pa.\nCLARION, Pa., August 19 JP\nThomas B. Slick, millionaire independ\nent oil operator of Oklahoma City,, J\nOkla., who died Saturday at Baltimore j\nat the age of 46, was buried yesterday i\nin the family plot in the Clarion Ceme-!\ntery after funeral services at the home\nof his mother. Mrs. Mary Slick.\nThe services were conducted by the i\nRev. P A. Galbraith, pastor of the j\nMethodist Episcopal Church, and many i\noil operators from the midcontinent i\nfield were present.\nSlick was born here and once oper-\nated in the Pennsylvania field. Later j\nhe operated in Southern Illinois, then 1\nin Oklahoma and Texas. He had gained I!\nthe reputation of \u201cKing of the Wild-11\ncattera\" and was reputed to be the\nweaffflwit independent operator in the\nworld.- j\nINQUIRY REVEALS\nFOOD RACKETEERS\nReluctant New York Wit\nnesses Tell Death Threats\nof Profiteers.\nBy th# Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. August 19.\u2014Evidence\nthat widespread organization of \u201cracket\neers. guerrillas and gangsters\u201d Is using\n\"strong-arm'\u2019 methods in New York\nCity to boost the cost of living was be\nfore State investigators today as they\npursued their inquiry into food profiteer-\ning.\nDespite reluctance of witnesses to\ntestify, and their stories that they had\nbeen threatened with ruin and death if\nthey refused to comply with the man\ndates of the racketeers. Assistant Attor\nney General William B. Groat. jr\u201e pre\ndicted more sensational revelations.\n\u201cYou've heard nothing compared to\nthe exposures that are coming,\" he said.\nMilk Ring Rejuvenated.\nTestimony elicited from two dozen\nwitnesses indicated the old Larry Pay\nmilk ring had been rejuvenated, and\nthat a \u201cmysterious\u201d organization was\nthreatening ruin to a large wholesale\nbusiness able and willing to lower egg\nprices here 5 cents a dozen.\nGroat asked Police Commissioner\nMulrooney to supply protection for the\nUtah Poultry Producers\u2019 Association\nafter Benjamin Brown, executive di\nrector in New York City, testified its\nbusiness was being ruined by the food\ncombination because it cut prices.\nEgg Warning Revealed.\nBrown testified that his association\ni had been delivering three carloads of\neggs a day in New York until a month\nj ago, and that its business was steadily\ngrowing until a stranger visited his\ni office and warned him not to interfere\nwith \u201cour market.\" He identified the\nvisitor as a Mr. Capelowich of the Vine\nland Butter Egg Co.\n\u201cYou better get wise and not butt\ninto the regular set-up in New York by\nselling direct to retail grocers,\u2019\u2019 Brown\nquoted Capelowich as saying. \u201cRemem\nber you hav? been warned.\u201d\nSeveral witnesses told of threats and\nvandalism by which they had been in\nduced to quit trading with the Utah\nassociation.\nTARIFF IS ISSUE\nOF FALL CAMPAIGN;\nSHOUSE OPENS FIRE\n(Continued From First Page.)\nof consumers, it developed, have been\nastonishingly few.\nIn the 60 days which have passed\nsince the enactment of the new tariff\nlaw they have amounted to only 21;\nand of these 21 there are orctably\nhalf which are directed toward revi\nsion upward rather than downward.\nAmong them, further, m spite of all\nthe emphatic protests made i gainst the\nnew law by foreign governments and\nby foreign associations of prod icers,\nthere is only one which represents for\neign complaint and foreign effort\ntoward revision downward. That is an\napplication on flaxseed by the Na\ntional Agricultural Society of Argen\ntina.\nThe President still has 30 days, under\nthe law, to appoint or reappoint the\nsix members of the Tariff Commission.\nIt is known that he has received several\nrefusals to serve from distinguished\nprivate citizens and it is believed with\nsome reason that it is doubtful it he\nhas so far secured a single firm accep\ntance. For reappointment fiom among\nthe present members of the commission\nstring public support has developed for\nAlfred Pearce Dennis. Democrat, of\nMaryland, and Edgar B. Brossard. Re\npublican, of Utah, both of whom, before\nthey entered public life, were by occupa\ntion economic students and college pro\nlessors.\n(Copyright, 1030.)\nBATTLE ON IN EARNEST.\nShouse Attacks Business Depression.\nTilson Predicts Overthrow.\nThe battle for control of Congress\nwas on in earnest today with the leading\nspokesmen of the Republican and Dem\nocratic parties recording their views of\nthe general issues on which the con\ntests is to be decided at the November\nelections.\nJouett Shouse. chairman of the Dem\nocratic National Executive Committee,\nplaced the Democratic side before the\ncountry in a radio address last night, in\nwhich the administration was charged\nwith errors both of omission and com\nmission. An immediate defense and\ncounter attack was issued in a state\nment to the press by John Q. Tilson of\nConnecticut, Republican floor leader in\nthe House of Representatives. Robert\nH. Lucas, executive director of the Re\npublican National Comimttee already\nwas on record with condemnation of the\nDemocratic position.\nHoover Drawn Into Blame.\nShouse's attack centered on the tariff\nbill, farm relief and business depression.\nPresident Hoover, in his speech, was\nmade to share responsibility with Con\ngress for the form taken by the tariff\nbill. He was singled out also for in\ndividual criticism in connection with ths\nfarm relief legislation adopted and for\nfailure to check in advance the depres\nsion which set in last Fall.\nTilson termed the Democratic speech\n\u201can amazing collection of half truths,\nmisstatements, abuse and criticism.\u201d\nShouse, said Tilson, \u201cfailed to suggest\na cure for a single thing which he criti\ncized. Instead of offering a construc\ntive program as his listeners had every\nright to expect him to do at this time,\n.P rpsen regrettable spectacle\nof the at least verbal leader of a politi\ncal Dirty literally gloating over th#\neconomic distress of the country.\u201d\nThe Democratic leader asserted the\npeople of the country \u201care arising to a\npolitical overthrow that may assure the\nproportions of a cataclysm.\u201d\nTilson replied that, overthrow of the\nRepublican party would be a \u201ccata\nclysm,\u201d because the party had \"a def\ninite well considered administrative\nand legislative program which it is car\nrying forward to completion despite the\ndetermined obstructive tactics of the\nDemocrats.\"\nDraws \u201cStolen Horse\u201d Parallel.\nShouse said farm products had de\nclined in price steadily since passage\nof the farm act. He contrasted the\nHoover 1928 campaign speeches assur\ning continuation of prosperity under\nRepublican rule with the unemployment\nand depressed business obtaining within\nthe year. He blamed the President for\nnot warning against speculation while\nSecretary of Commerce and President\nelect. Conceding that after the crash\nMr. Hoover \"did perhaps all any man\ncould to try to effect an adjustment\nof conditions.\u201d Shouse observed that\n\u201chistory is apt to record 'that he locked\nthe barn door after the horse was\nstolen.\u2019\nHe said President Hoover could have\nchecked the tariff \u201craid\u201d at any time\nduring the long period the revision was\nunder congressional consideration, but\nhad failed to speak the word which\nwould have \"corrected the intolerable\nFeatures of this unholy and excuseless\npiece of legislation.\u201d\nPointing to Shouse\u2019s assertion that\nthe Democrats would endeavor to re\nspond to the people\u2019s \u201ccries of despera\ntion\" for relief from present condi\ntions. Tilson challenged the opposition\nleaders to show how they would \u201cen\ndeavor to respond.\"\n\"Will \u2018a sympathetic and understand\nng ear\u2019 cure the ill* of which Mr\nShouse complains?\u201d he asked. \u201cIf *o\nlow?\u201d\n\u201cThese are pertinent questions tat\nvhlch the voters certainly have tb*\nIffht to an answer in this campalcn.\u2019*","height":"25545","width":"19842"}}
